1x 2 - <a href="javascript:card_browser(207)">Bree Gate</a><br>
1x 1 - <a href="javascript:card_browser(201)">East Road</a>    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Card Switch: Pathfinder for Thror&#39;s Map<br>
Bid = 0<br>
<br><br>
Fellowship Strategy:<br>
<br><br>
Ok, first of this deck is a partial choke because there is only frodo, boromir and aragorn in the fellowship but I don&#39;t play with any twilight denial because that&#39;s not this decks strategy.  Depend on drawing Aragorn to get him out, early one Boromir can protect Frodo because shadow gets minimum twilight.  This deck is designed to have Boromir and Aragorn win skirmishes thereby taking few wounds if any.  At the early sites you should not be taking any damage from skirmishes because they&#39;ll be seriously limited in twilight.  Late game is where the strength boosters (swordarm of white tower and swordsman of the northern kingdom) come into play.  Cards like Elendil&#39;s Valor pump up the two men and saga of Elendil gives them each a boost to health and strength when needed.  Armor and Athelas is for later game when they might not be winning combat.  Thror&#39;s map can make sure you set up the site you want to use usually save for site 8 or 9.  Gondor&#39;s vengeance and pursuit just behind is to eliminate stragglers as you double move along.  Ranger&#39;s versatility of course comes in very handy.  Saruman&#39;s Snows does have a slim affect on the deck but you can take a few hits of damage so one battle without winning a skirmish is quite fine.  Until anti-skirmishing cards become more popular I don&#39;t find them much of a threat.<br>
<br><br>
Shadow Strategy:<br>
<br><br>
Basics of the deck is to cause exertion or burden to the ring-bearer (via. cruel caradhras and worry) late game is when traitor&#39;s voice comes into play to prevent thoughts of a double move by opponent.  Bred for battle is 0 cost and boosts your uruk-hai so overwhelming can become more common.  The uruk-hai minions all have good health 3+ except spy which is in there for burdening in combination with Saruman&#39;s reach.  Saruman&#39;s reach is a great card once spy is out with some other minions at site 7-9.  Most likely opponent won&#39;t want to exert 2 companions so will likely put on the ring, if played right you can have this occur when Frodo is fighting and do double damage.  Other bonuses are the free archer damage you get from assasin and lurtz.  I realize the cost of the chosen minions are slightly high 7,5,5,4,2 but with the strength boosting one minion can still cause damage to a companion.  The high health is also a preventative for archery.<br>
<br><br>
Site Strategy:<br>
East Road - cause if you start this limits big companion parties from playing out right away.<br>
Bree Gate - let&#39;s you jump ahead of your opponent early.<br>
Rivendell Waterfall - Again moving around fast.<br>
Pass Of Caradhras - Works well with the shadow side, getting out the weather events.<br>
Bridge of Khazad-dum - To kick fellowship hiney with good twilight.<br>
Lothlorien Woods - Only site which didn&#39;t have extremely detrimental effects to my shadow except against an elf deck (may switch to Lothlorien Glade depending on playtesting)<br>
Pillars of The Kings - River, healing for my warriors and low twilight for a site 8.<br>
Tol Brandir - River, basically only reason, sure slopes help my shadow but by this time i should be in the lead and i&#39;d rather have the advantage for fellowship.<br>
<br><br>
Thanks for taking the time to review the deck.<br>
<br><br>
